ght to strike must be protected. He challenges the current "law turn" in labor scholarship and takes into account the role of party alliances, administrative agencies, the military, and the rise of modern presidential powers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEmployee rightszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndustrial relationszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor laws and legislationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor unionszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aStrikes and lockoutszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aLabor History. 4aU.S. History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172752840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501727528423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501727528/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles